12/10/2004
LUXEMBOURG -- The EU foreign ministers on Monday (11 October) approved operational plans for the deployment of 7,000 troops in Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH), to take over peacekeeping operations from NATO. 
The force, named "Althea", would be the Union's largest military undertaking to date. 
At the Monday meeting, the EU Ministerial Council also decided to extend by one year the EU police mission in Macedonia, whose mandate was set to expire on 15 December.
In other news, an operational exercise involving NATO forces in BiH and Kosovo began Monday. 
SFOR says it is aimed at ensuring preparedness of NATO peacekeepers and the Reserve Forces Staff to tackle possible crises in the region. 
(AFP, AP, Fena, ABC News, Pincom.info - 11/10/04)
